e la Loire, France":"Laval, Mayenne, France","Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Champagne-Ardenne, France","Dinan, Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany, France":"Dinan, Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Laval","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: topographic name for someone who lived in a valley, Old French <i>val</i> (originally feminine, later masculine; see   Val  , compare   Lavallee  ), or a habitational name from Laval, the name of several places in various parts of France, ultimately derived from Latin <i>vallis</i> ‘valley’."],"variants":[{"name":"Val","meanings":["Spanish: variant of   Valle  , from <i>val</i>, a variant of <i>valle</i> ‘valley’. Compare   Delval  .","Galician and Portuguese: topographic name for someone who lived in a valley, <i>val</i> (compare 3 below). Compare also   Doval  .","French and Haitian: topographic name for someone who lived in a valley, (Old) French <i>val</i> (originally feminine, later masculine; compare   Vallee  ), from Latin <i>vallis</i> (feminine). Compare   Duval   and   Laval  ."]}]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adèle de Laval was born in 1040, in Laval, Mayenne, France, her father, Guy de Laval, was 41 and her mother, Berthe de Tosny, was 38. She married Giron II d'Acigné de Chateaugiron. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1040–":"1040–Surnud","1027–Female":"1027–Surnud","1029–Female":"1029–Surnud","1033–Female":"1033–Surnud","1035–1080":"1035–1080","1037–Female":"1037–Surnud","1040–Female":"1040–Surnud","–1026":"–1026","1035–1070":"1035–1070","1069–1147":"1069–1147","1000–1065":"1000–1065","1002–1090":"1002–1090","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1000":"1000","1033":"1033","1065":"1065","1040":"1040","1070":"1070","1029":"1029","1027":"1027","1147":"1147","1026":"1026","1037":"1037","1069":"1069","1002":"1002","1035":"1035","about 1069":"umbes 1069","about 1023":"umbes 1023","Laval, Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France":"Laval, Mayenne, Prantsusmaa","Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Champagne-Ardenne, Prantsusmaa","Dinan, Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany, France":"Dinan, Côtes-d'Armor, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1040–":"1040–Kuollut","1027–Female":"1027–Kuollut","1029–Female":"1029–Kuollut","1033–Female":"1033–Kuollut","1035–1080":"1035–1080","1037–Female":"1037–Kuollut","1040–Female":"1040–Kuollut","–1026":"–1026","1035–1070":"1035–1070","1069–1147":"1069–1147","1000–1065":"1000–1065","1002–1090":"1002–1090","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1000":"1000","1033":"1033","1065":"1065","1040":"1040","1070":"1070","1029":"1029","1027":"1027","1147":"1147","1026":"1026","1037":"1037","1069":"1069","1002":"1002","1035":"1035","about 1069":"noin 1069","about 1023":"noin 1023","Laval, Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France":"Laval, Mayenne, Ranska","Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Champagne-Ardenne, Ranska","Dinan, Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany, France":"Dinan, Côtes-d'Armor, Bretagne, Ranska"},"fr":{"1040–":"1040–Décédée","1027–Female":